[
    {
        "content": "<p>In <a href=\"#narrow/stream/304641-ideas/topic/List.2Erange.20boundaries\">the conversation on <code>List.range</code></a>, we decided to merge multiple <code>range</code>-related proposals <code>List.rangeInclusive</code>, <code>List.rangeExclusive</code>, <code>List.rangeBy</code> into one function with a rich input that captures all of that nuance. What if we explored merging other builtin functions in a similar way?</p>\n<p>For example, we currently have</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Haskell\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kt\">List</span><span class=\"o\">.</span><span class=\"n\">sortAsc</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">List</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"kt\">Num</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">a</span><span class=\"p\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"ow\">-&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">List</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"kt\">Num</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">a</span><span class=\"p\">)</span><span class=\"w\"></span>\n<span class=\"kt\">List</span><span class=\"o\">.</span><span class=\"n\">sortDesc</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">List</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"kt\">Num</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">a</span><span class=\"p\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"ow\">-&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">List</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"kt\">Num</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">a</span><span class=\"p\">)</span><span class=\"w\"></span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>but why not</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Haskell\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kt\">List</span><span class=\"o\">.</span><span class=\"n\">sort</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">List</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"kt\">Num</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">a</span><span class=\"p\">),</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">[</span><span class=\"kt\">Asc</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Desc</span><span class=\"p\">]</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"ow\">-&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">List</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"kt\">Num</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">a</span><span class=\"p\">)</span><span class=\"w\"></span>\n</code></pre></div>",
        "id": 303101768,
        "sender_full_name": "jan kili",
        "timestamp": 1665301874
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>From</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Haskell\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kt\">Str</span><span class=\"o\">.</span><span class=\"n\">replaceEach</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Str</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Str</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Str</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"ow\">-&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Result</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Str</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">[</span><span class=\"kt\">NotFound</span><span class=\"p\">]</span><span class=\"o\">*</span><span class=\"w\"></span>\n<span class=\"kt\">Str</span><span class=\"o\">.</span><span class=\"n\">replaceFirst</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Str</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Str</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Str</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"ow\">-&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Result</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Str</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">[</span><span class=\"kt\">NotFound</span><span class=\"p\">]</span><span class=\"o\">*</span><span class=\"w\"></span>\n<span class=\"kt\">Str</span><span class=\"o\">.</span><span class=\"n\">replaceLast</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Str</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Str</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Str</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"ow\">-&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Result</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Str</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">[</span><span class=\"kt\">NotFound</span><span class=\"p\">]</span><span class=\"o\">*</span><span class=\"w\"></span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>to</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Haskell\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kt\">Str</span><span class=\"o\">.</span><span class=\"n\">replace</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Str</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">[</span><span class=\"kt\">Each</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">First</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Last</span><span class=\"p\">],</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Str</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Str</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"ow\">-&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Result</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Str</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">[</span><span class=\"kt\">NotFound</span><span class=\"p\">]</span><span class=\"o\">*</span><span class=\"w\"></span>\n</code></pre></div>",
        "id": 303102077,
        "sender_full_name": "jan kili",
        "timestamp": 1665302157
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I see a lot of sets of related builtins like <code>Hash.addBytes</code>/<code>addI8</code>/<code>addU16</code>/<code>add*</code> or <code>Num.toU8</code>/<code>toU8Checked</code>/<code>to*</code> that <strong><em>seem</em></strong> like strong contenders for this, but their return types are inherently <strong><em>different</em></strong> (either containing a concrete numeric type or sometimes wrapping the return type in a <code>Result</code> for fallibility). Therefore, I think the criteria here should be \"builtin functions with related functionality, similar names, and identical return types should be merged by adding a tag union input parameter\".</p>",
        "id": 303102935,
        "sender_full_name": "jan kili",
        "timestamp": 1665302866
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Thoughts? Does this look very elegant to anyone else?</p>",
        "id": 303103017,
        "sender_full_name": "jan kili",
        "timestamp": 1665302924
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>From</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Haskell\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"p\">[</span><span class=\"mi\">1</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">5</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">2</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">4</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">3</span><span class=\"p\">]</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">|&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">List</span><span class=\"o\">.</span><span class=\"n\">sortAsc</span><span class=\"w\"></span>\n<span class=\"s\">\"1 5 2 4 3\"</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">|&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Str</span><span class=\"o\">.</span><span class=\"n\">replaceEach</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"s\">\" \"</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"s\">\", \"</span><span class=\"w\"></span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>to</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Haskell\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"p\">[</span><span class=\"mi\">1</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">5</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">2</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">4</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">3</span><span class=\"p\">]</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">|&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">List</span><span class=\"o\">.</span><span class=\"n\">sort</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Asc</span><span class=\"w\"></span>\n<span class=\"s\">\"1 5 2 4 3\"</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">|&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Str</span><span class=\"o\">.</span><span class=\"n\">replace</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Each</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"s\">\" \"</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"s\">\", \"</span><span class=\"w\"></span>\n</code></pre></div>",
        "id": 303103498,
        "sender_full_name": "jan kili",
        "timestamp": 1665303283
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>(in these examples, the only syntactical cost to app developers is the addition of a single space character, but I'm optimistic about the conceptual benefits of self-documenting alternatives and the flexibility of toggling behavior with a tag variable instead of switching function calls)</p>",
        "id": 303103552,
        "sender_full_name": "jan kili",
        "timestamp": 1665303340
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It does noticeably complicate type signatures...<br>\nLots of new roc programmers will not be familiar with anything like our tags. I think this will add a noticeable difficulty to getting started with roc.</p>",
        "id": 303118747,
        "sender_full_name": "Anton",
        "timestamp": 1665313417
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>yeah my default preference is to have more, simpler functions</p>",
        "id": 303120126,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1665314282
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think <code>List.range</code> is unusual in that it is notoriously easy to accidentally misuse</p>",
        "id": 303120217,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1665314318
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>so I think in its case, there's a benefit to having one function with arguments that make the subtly different alternatives clear</p>",
        "id": 303120262,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1665314365
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>which is not a problem most functions have</p>",
        "id": 303120279,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1665314378
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>incidentally this preference is part of why Roc doesn't have default arguments</p>",
        "id": 303120592,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1665314544
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>languages with default arguments typically would let you do either <code>Str.join strings</code> or <code>Str.join strings \", \"</code></p>",
        "id": 303120687,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1665314609
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>with the second argument being optional and defaulting to either <code>\"\"</code> or <code>\" \"</code></p>",
        "id": 303120782,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1665314653
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>but I'd rather have <code>Str.join</code> and <code>Str.joinWith</code> that each do one thing</p>",
        "id": 303120811,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1665314681
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>instead of having the more complicated function being the only thing you can reach for, with the simpler <code>Str.join : List Str -&gt; Str</code> being unavailable</p>",
        "id": 303120847,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1665314728
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I like being able to reach for something with the simplest type that will get the job done for me, and only looking further for something more complicated when the simplest thing won't meet my needs (which it often will)</p>",
        "id": 303120991,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1665314809
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>it also facilitates a nicer documentation reading experience: I can learn about the simplest operation by reading docs that are scoped narrowly too, and then discover the more complicated ones by links like \"To insert a string in between each of the joined strings, use <code>Str.joinWith</code>\"</p>",
        "id": 303121445,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1665315100
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think it is also very important to note that tags can have a costs. For example, if <code>List.range</code> doesn't get inlined, you will be spending extra time twiddling with memory on every function call to create the tags. Then you will be spending extra time in the function matching on the tag and pulling the data back out. As such, i would be careful about doing this conversion to any complex functions. Otherwise we would be accidentally slowing down every function we do this too.</p>",
        "id": 303141469,
        "sender_full_name": "Brendan Hansknecht",
        "timestamp": 1665326991
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>to be fair, I think it's safe to assume it'll get inlined</p>",
        "id": 303144480,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1665329012
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>(if it doesn't automatically, we can make sure it does because it's a builtin)</p>",
        "id": 303144521,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1665329042
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>For <code>List.range</code> sure, it is small. For other builtins that are larger, it may not be reasonable to inline them.</p>",
        "id": 303152872,
        "sender_full_name": "Brendan Hansknecht",
        "timestamp": 1665334387
    }
]